<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a1252.g.akamaitech.net/7/1252/34/dd3ed3b3a12b09/dsc.discovery.com/news/briefs/20010827/gallery/marscar_goto.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
To get over large rocks, the rover needs high clearance, a flexible frame, a very high torque drive train, and ultra-low gearing to crawl like a bug over obstacles.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://dsc.discovery.com/news/briefs/20010827/marscar.html">Martian Cars.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
But what if you need to live in the rover for two weeks while out rockhounding in the Martian countryside? Rovers will need their own air supply, living quarters and energy enough to keep moving more than a hundred million miles from the nearest filling station.<br>
<br>
Nuclear power or fuel cells are the logical power plants, said Chad Ohlandt, a Ph.D. engineering student at Michigan State University. Solar power won't work, he said, because rovers are too small to put enough solar panels on and the sunshine on Mars is pretty weak. Solar cells are also too fragile for the harsh Martian environment.<br>
